---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { atlas } from '../utils/atlas';
const a = atlas();
const stateCount = a.nationStates.size;
const doctrineCount = a.doctrines.size;
const actorCount = a.actors.size;
const eventCount = a.events.size;
const earliestYear = [...a.events.values()]
  .map((e) => parseInt((e.start_date ?? e.disclosure_date ?? '').slice(0, 4), 10))
  .filter((y) => Number.isFinite(y))
  .reduce((min, y) => Math.min(min, y), 9999);
---
<Base title="About">
  <p class="kicker">About</p>
  <h1 style="margin-top:0;">Doctrine before attribution</h1>

  <p class="lede">
    AUSPEX is a doctrine-tagged atlas of state-sponsored cyber events,
    published by Black Flag Intelligence. The name is the Roman augur
    who read signs to advise the senate before military action — the
    same job, in a different age.
  </p>

  <h2>The wedge</h2>
  <p>
    Vendor threat intel — Mandiant, Microsoft, CrowdStrike, Recorded
    Future — indexes <em>what</em>, <em>who</em>, and <em>how</em>: IOCs,
    TTPs, attributed actors. Strategic-studies institutions — CSIS,
    RUSI, RAND — index the <em>why</em>: doctrines, grand strategies,
    timeline pressures. Nobody indexes events <em>against</em>
    doctrines as a first-class data model. That join is the product.
  </p>

  <h2>The model</h2>
  <p>
    Every event in the atlas can carry any number of doctrine links,
    each with its own confidence label and reasoning. A single
    pre-positioning intrusion may serve Taiwan-reunification doctrine
    <em>and</em> Military-Civil Fusion's civil-infrastructure-targeting
    pillar at different confidence levels backed by different sources.
    The model exposes that complexity rather than collapsing it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Crucially: <strong>a doctrine link can stand without an attributed
    actor</strong>. When the victim, the timing, and the technique fit
    a doctrine pillar but no public attribution has been made, we still
    tag — at <em>plausible</em> or <em>strongly inferred</em>
    confidence — and we say why. That's the black-flag cell, and it's
    where AUSPEX is most useful.
  </p>

  <h2>The atlas</h2>
  <p>
    Atlas v0 covers {stateCount} nation-states, {doctrineCount} doctrines,
    {actorCount} named cyber actors, and {eventCount} events from {earliestYear}
    onward. Coverage is hand-curated, source-anchored, and revised in
    public. The structured atlas is regenerated from YAML on every
    build; primary sources are linked from every claim.
  </p>

  <h2>Confidence labels</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <span class="confidence confidence-attested">attested</span>
      &mdash; the attributing government or vendor explicitly named the
      strategic goal. Highest standard.
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="confidence confidence-strongly-inferred">strongly inferred</span>
      &mdash; victim sector, timing, and actor mission align with a
      named doctrine pillar with no major alternative explanation.
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="confidence confidence-plausible">plausible</span>
      &mdash; fits the doctrine, but other explanations exist. Flagged
      for analyst review and presented with the alternative.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Not affiliated</h2>
  <p>
    AUSPEX is independent. We do not work for, contract with, or take
    funding from any government, intelligence service, or vendor named
    in the atlas. We rely on open-source primary materials: official
    disclosures, indictments, sanctions actions, CERT advisories, and
    peer-reviewed vendor research. When sources disagree, we say so.
  </p>

  <h2>Contact</h2>
  <p>
    <a href="mailto:auspex@blackflagintel.com">auspex@blackflagintel.com</a>
  </p>
</Base>
